<%- include('partials/header.ejs') %>

<section class="stage-banner">
	<div class="container">
		<div class="stage-header">
			<div>
				<p class="section-label">Stage Two</p>
				<h1 class="section-title">The Investigative Cycle</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p class="section-intro">
			Once you've been referred and seen by a fertility specialist, the investigative cycle begins.
			This is the phase where your medical team runs tests to identify what might be affecting your fertility.
			Some tests can be done anytime, but others must be timed to specific days of your menstrual cycle, which means
			you'll likely visit the clinic multiple times across one or two cycles. Here's what each test is for, when it
			happens, and why your team needs it.
		</p>

		<div class="text-center my-3">
			<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/percentage_maker_3.png" alt="Image Explain-Infertility is not just a
			female issue. About 30% of cases are due to male factors, 40% to female factors, and the
			remaining 30% involve a combination of both or remain unexplained." class="infertility-img desktop-img" >
			<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/percentage_maker_narrow.png" alt="Image Explain-Infertility is not just a
			female issue. About 30% of cases are due to male factors, 40% to female factors, and the
			remaining 30% involve a combination of both or remain unexplained." class="infertility-img mobile-img" >
		</div>

		<%- include('partials/stage2-steps') %>

		<div class="highlight-box">
			<h6 class="highlight-box_title">What to keep in mind when booking</h6>
			<ul class="highlight-box_list">
				<li>
					<strong>Blood work and routine ultrasounds</strong> are usually easy to book and often available
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Tests that require a doctor</strong> (like the sonohysterogram) depend on their schedule. 
					If the doctor isn't available during your cycle window, the test gets pushed to your next cycle.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

<section class="section-light">
	<div class="container">

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>Common Tests & What They're For During the Investigative Cycle</h4>
			<p>
				The timeline below follows your menstrual cycle. <strong>Day 1 is the first day of your period</strong>, 
				and all other days are counted from there.
			</p>
			<div class="timeline">

				<!-- Day 3 -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="day3">
					<h5>Cycle Day 3</h5>
					<p>This is your first and busiest clinic visit. Expect to be there for a while as multiple tests are done on the same day.</p>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--green">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/needle_4_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<strong>Screening Blood Work + Hormone Panel</strong>
							<p>
								Around 6 vials of blood covering various blood levels, immunities, hepatitis, and infectious disease testing 
								including HIV. At the same time, your hormone panel will be drawn to assess ovarian function, thyroid health, 
								and hormonal balance. <br><br>This typically includes FSH (Follicle Stimulating Hormone), LH (Luteinizing Hormone), 
								Estradiol, TSH (Thyroid Stimulating Hormone), and Prolactin.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--orange">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/ultrasound_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<strong>Baseline Ultrasound</strong>
							<p>
								This appointment starts with an external (transabdominal) ultrasound, which requires a full bladder 
								for clear imaging. Plan to drink about 3 to 4 cups of water (roughly 700 ml to 1 litre) and finish 
								about an hour before your appointment. Do not use the washroom until after the external scan is 
								complete. You will then be asked to empty your bladder, and your doctor will perform an internal 
								(transvaginal) ultrasound. <br><br>Together, these scans check the number of follicles in your ovaries, uterine lining, 
								and look for any structural abnormalities like fibroids or cysts. An additional 1 tube of blood 
								may also be drawn.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Sono -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="sono">
					<h5>Cycle Day 5 to 11: Sono (Sonohysterogram)</h5>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--navy">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/doctor_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<p>
								Saline is injected into the uterus while an internal ultrasound is performed to check for structural abnormalities 
								such as polyps, fibroids, or other uterine issues. This test needs to be scheduled within a specific window of your 
								cycle. You will likely be advised to take 2 over-the-counter pain relievers about an hour before your appointment 
								to help with discomfort.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Cycle Monitoring -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="cycle-monitoring">
					<h5>Cycle Day 10 to 18: Cycle Monitoring</h5>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--orange">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/ultrasound_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<p>
								Starting around day 10, you will visit the clinic every other day for an internal (transvaginal) ultrasound and blood 
								work. Your medical team is monitoring the hormones involved in follicle development to pinpoint the time of ovulation. 
								The number of visits varies from person to person, and your nurse will let you know when to come back each time.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Progesterone -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="progesterone">
					<h5>Around Cycle Day 20: P4 / Progesterone</h5>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--green">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/needle_4_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<p>
								One vial of blood to confirm whether ovulation has occurred. Due to varying individual cycle lengths, your nurse will 
								confirm the specific date it should be drawn.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Beta HCG -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="beta-hcg">
					<h5>Around Cycle Day 28: Beta HCG / Pregnancy Test <span class="optional-label">(Optional)</span></h5>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--green timeline-icon--optional">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/needle_4_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<p>
								This test is only scheduled if you've discussed with your doctor that you want to try conceiving naturally during the 
								investigative cycle. If that's the case, around Day 28 your clinic will draw one vial of blood to check your Beta HCG 
								level and confirm whether the cycle resulted in pregnancy. Due to varying individual cycle lengths, your nurse will 
								confirm the specific date it should be drawn.</p>
							<p>If you're not actively trying to conceive during this cycle, this test is usually skipped.

							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Anytime tests -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="anytime-tests">
					<h5>Tests that can be done any time</h5>
					<p>These tests can be scheduled independently of your menstrual cycle, which gives you more flexibility in timing.</p>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--green">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/needle_4_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<strong>AMH (Anti-Müllerian Hormone)</strong>
							<p>A single vial of blood that measures your ovarian reserve. Can be drawn on any day of your cycle.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--green">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/needle_4_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<strong>Vitamin D</strong>
							<p>A blood test to check your vitamin D levels, since low vitamin D may negatively affect fertility outcomes.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--charcoal">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/analysis_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<strong>Comprehensive Semen Analysis with Strict Morphology</strong>
							<p>
								If you have a male partner, they will need to provide a semen sample for analysis. This test evaluates sperm count, 
								motility, and morphology (shape) using strict criteria. Your partner will need to abstain for at least 3 days before 
								the test, and an appointment must be booked in advance.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Review -->
				<div class="timeline-item" id="review">
					<h5>After Day 21: Review Appointment</h5>

					<div class="timeline-item-row">
						<div class="timeline-icon timeline-icon--navy">
							<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/doctor_144w.png" alt="">
						</div>
						<div class="timeline-item-text">
							<p>
								Only after completing your first investigative cycle and all required testing, you will be asked to book a review 
								appointment with your doctor. This should be scheduled after day 21 and before your next period. During this 
								appointment, your doctor will go over your results, discuss what they mean for your situation, and create a plan for 
								your next treatment cycle. The review can be done through an online video call or in person at the clinic.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="highlight-box">
			<strong>Why does this take so long?</strong> Not all tests can be done in the same cycle. Some are
			time-sensitive (e.g., blood work on day 3, Sono mid-cycle). If scheduling doesn't align, you may wait
			another month. This is normal but frustrating, and it's why knowing the timeline upfront helps manage expectations.
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>Common Questions During the Investigative Cycle</h4>
			<p>
				Whether this is your first cycle of testing or you're a few weeks in, here are some of the questions people often
				have along the way.
			</p>

			<div class="qa-block">
				<div class="qa-block_question" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#qa1" aria-expanded="false">
					<h5>How long does the whole investigative cycle take?</h5>
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/down_arrow.png" alt="toggle open button" class="qa-block_icon">
				</div>
				<div id="qa1" class="collapse">
					<div class="qa-block_answer">
						<p>
							Most people complete the full set of tests in one menstrual cycle, but it often spreads across two cycles if
							scheduling doesn't line up. Tests like the sonohysterogram require a doctor's availability during a specific
							window, and missing that window means waiting until the next cycle. Plan for one to two months from your
							first appointment to your review.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="qa-block">
				<div class="qa-block_question" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#qa2" aria-expanded="false">
					<h5>Why do I have to come back so many times?</h5>
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/down_arrow.png" alt="toggle open button" class="qa-block_icon">
				</div>
				<div id="qa2" class="collapse">
					<div class="qa-block_answer">
						<p>
							Different tests need to happen at different points in your cycle because they measure different things.
							Day 3 hormones show your baseline. Mid-cycle ultrasounds track follicle growth. Around Day 20 progesterone
							confirms whether ovulation actually happened. There's no single visit that can capture all of this, which
							is why the visits add up.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

    <div class="qa-block">
        <div class="qa-block_question" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#qa3" aria-expanded="false">
            <h5>What if I miss a Day 3 appointment or my cycle is irregular?</h5>
            <img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/down_arrow.png" alt="toggle open button" class="qa-block_icon">
        </div>
        <div id="qa3" class="collapse">
            <div class="qa-block_answer">
                <p>
                    If you miss a Day 3 window, your clinic will reschedule the test for your next cycle. Irregular cycles are
                    common and your team is used to working around them. Let your nurse know as soon as possible so they can adjust
                    the plan. You're not behind, and missing a day doesn't undo any progress.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="qa-block">
        <div class="qa-block_question" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#qa4" aria-expanded="false">
            <h5>What happens if I need to switch clinics partway through?</h5>
            <img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/down_arrow.png" alt="toggle open button" class="qa-block_icon">
        </div>
        <div id="qa4" class="collapse">
            <div class="qa-block_answer">
                <p>
                    Whether you're moving, changing jobs, or simply not happy with your current clinic, switching is more common
                    , and more straightforward, than you might think. You don't have to start from scratch. The general process:
                    ask your family doctor for a new referral to the clinic you want, and the new clinic will request your records
                    from the old one.
                </p>
                <p>Most clinics will accept your previous test results, though they may want to repeat certain tests if too much
                    time has passed (for example, AMH results are typically considered valid for around 6 months, and infectious
                    disease screenings within 6 to 12 months). If you're staying in Ontario, OHIP-covered tests remain covered no
                    matter which clinic you go to, even if you have to repeat some. Out-of-pocket tests like AMH ($105) and
                    Vitamin D ($75) would need to be paid again if repeated.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <strong>One practical tip:</strong> when transferring records, request a copy be sent to you as well, not just
                    to the new clinic. Records sometimes get sent incompletely between clinics, and you don't want to discover
                    something is missing at your first appointment.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If you're moving to another province or country, you'll be working with a different healthcare system entirely,
                    so plan ahead and ask your current clinic for a full copy of your records before you leave.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

	<div class="qa-block">
		<div class="qa-block_question" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#qa5" aria-expanded="false">
			<h5>What will I have to pay out of pocket during the investigative cycle?</h5>
			<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/down_arrow.png" alt="" class="qa-block_icon">
		</div>
		<div id="qa5" class="collapse">
			<div class="qa-block_answer">
				<p>
					Most tests during the investigative cycle are covered by OHIP, but a few are not. 
					Here's a quick breakdown of the common out-of-pocket costs:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>AMH (Anti-Müllerian Hormone):</strong> <span class="orange-text">$105</span> per person</li>
					<li><strong>Vitamin D blood test:</strong>  <span class="orange-text">$75</span> per person</li>
					<li><strong>Comprehensive Semen Analysis:</strong> <span class="orange-text">$160</span> per person</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					If  both you and your male partner <strong>complete all non-covered tests</strong>  including Vitamin D for 
					both of you, expect to pay around  <span class="orange-text">$415</span> in total. 
					Prices may vary slightly by clinic. If you switch clinics and need to repeat any of 
					these tests, you will need to pay again.
				</p>
				</p>
				<p>
					<strong>Potential cost, Prenatal vitamins: </strong> if you're trying to conceive, your family doctor or fertility 
					specialist may recommend a prenatal multivitamin to support egg and overall reproductive health. 
					This is not mandatory, but is commonly suggested. In Canada, doctors often prescribe PregVit, and 
					will recommend the appropriate folic acid dosage based on your individual needs.
				</p>
				<p>
					Prenatal vitamins typically cost around <span class="orange-text">$120</span> per month and are not covered by provincial health insurance. However, 
					some private insurance plans, such as 
					<a href="https://www.canadalife.com" target="_blank">Canada Life</a>, 
					<a href="https://www.sunlife.ca" target="_blank">Sun Life</a>, 
					<a href="https://www.manulife.ca" target="_blank">Manulife</a>, 
					<a href="https://www.bluecross.ca" target="_blank">Blue Cross</a>, 
					<a href="https://www.desjardins.com/insurance" target="_blank">Desjardins</a>, and 
					<a href="https://www.greenshield.ca" target="_blank">Green Shield Canada</a>, 
					may partially or fully cover prescribed prenatal vitamins depending on your 
					specific plan. Check with your employer's benefits provider to find out.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

</div>
		<%- include('partials/quiz-stage2') %>
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-between mt-5">
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/stage1" class="btn btn-outline-sage">← Stage 1: Before the GP</a>
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/stage3" class="btn btn-outline-sage">Next: Treatment & Funding →</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

</main>
